The same code used to work with prior versions of LibGDX and RoboVM. Same code works fine in DEBUG mode, it crashes in release mode on both the Simulator (iPhone-5s - 9.2 on x86_64) and on devices (iPod *, iPhones *).
- Is there any limitation with RoboVM in term of using final keywords or anonymous inner class?
- Is it possible that the instance got GC'ed due to a specific GC implemented in RoboVM that would not respect the JVM GC behavior? Is it a mark & sweep implementation that takes into account final variables assigned

Here is the stacktrace of code that leads to NPE:

java.lang.NullPointerException
    at uniwar.scene.game.CreateCustomOnlineGameScene$12.run(CreateCustomOnlineGameScene.java:390)
....

```
private void gameCreatedSuccessfully(final NewGame newGame) {
    final DialogScene scene = DialogScene.getInfoScene(Texts.GAME_SUCCESSFULLY_CREATED);
    scene.actionToPerformOnDismiss = new Runnable() {
        @Override
        public void run() {
            scene.removeScene();
            if (newGame.saveRequested) { // <== CAUSES NPE but newGame is not null
                newGame.setAllPlayerSeats(GamePlayer.Seat.OPEN);
                newGame.save();
            }
            Stage.setScene(canvas.currentGamesScene);
        }
    };
    Stage.pushScene(scene);
}

private void createGame() {
    newGame.name = nameSprite.textField.getText();
    if (newGame.name.length() <= 0) {
        DialogScene.showErrorScene(Texts.INVALID_GAME_NAME);
        return;
    }
    if (newGame.saveRequested) {
        newGame.save();
    }
    final CommandCreateGame command = new CommandCreateGame(newGame);
    command.addListener(new CommandResultListener() {
        @Override
        public void commandPerformed(boolean success) {
            if (success) {
                canvas.currentGamesScene.requestDownload();
                gameCreatedSuccessfully(command.newGame); // command.newGame is final too
            }
        }
    });
    command.showScene();
}
```

Since libGDX version 1.7.2, `BitmapFont` draws out of bounds when the first character has a negative `xoffset`. Version 1.7.1 does not show this issue.

Here is an example app showing a `Label` with a red background:

![example](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5756227/12483853/8cc2852c-c057-11e5-8e82-a55941fe1c48.png)

``` java
public class TestGame extends ApplicationAdapter {
    private Stage stage;
    private BitmapFont font;

    @Override
    public void create() {
        font = new BitmapFont(Gdx.files.internal("Chewy_80.fnt"));
        font.getRegion().getTexture().setFilter(TextureFilter.Linear, TextureFilter.Linear);

        Pixmap pixmap = new Pixmap(1, 1, Pixmap.Format.RGBA8888);
        pixmap.setColor(Color.RED);
        pixmap.fill();
        Texture texture = new Texture(pixmap);
        pixmap.dispose();

        LabelStyle style = new LabelStyle(font, Color.WHITE);
        style.background = new TextureRegionDrawable(new TextureRegion(texture));

        Label label = new Label("Test", style);
        label.setPosition(32, 32);

        stage = new Stage(new FitViewport(200, 200));
        stage.addActor(label);
    }

    @Override
    public void resize(int width, int height) {
        stage.getViewport().update(width, height, true);
    }

    @Override
    public void render() {
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(0.5f, 0.5f, 0.5f, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);

        stage.act();
        stage.draw();
    }

    @Override
    public void dispose() {
        stage.dispose();
        font.dispose();
    }
}
```

I also included the bitmap font used for this test: [Chewy_bitmap.zip](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/files/99316/Chewy_bitmap.zip)

I'm not sure whether this is related to issue #3472, but if it is, this still seemed to be worth a separate bug report.

